'''Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko''' (дёҠжө·дёҠеӣҪйҖ , also known as Kamitsu Unakami KokuzЕҚ) governed the {{ill|KaijЕҚ District, Kazusa Province|ja|жө·дёҠйғЎ (дёҠз·ҸеӣҪ)|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kazusa Province|ja|дёҠз·ҸеӣҪ|12=draft}}, which corresponds to part of present-day {{ill|Ichihara|ja|еёӮеҺҹеёӮ|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|еҚғи‘үзңҢ|12=draft}}. It is also referred to as Kamitsu Unakami KokuzЕҚ.
== Overview == The region surrounding the {{ill|YЕҚrЕҚ River|ja|йӨҠиҖҒе·қ|12=draft}} basin features archaeological sites such as the {{ill|Kamado Kofun Cluster|ja|зҘһй–ҖеҸӨеўізҫӨ|12=draft}}, believed to be early 3rd-century keyhole-shaped tombs ({{ill|ZenpЕҚ-kЕҚen-fun|ja|еүҚж–№еҫҢеҶҶеўі|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}}),<ref>This interpretation as kofun shifts the beginning of the Kofun period significantly earlier. Others suggest these are late {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|ејҘз”ҹжҷӮд»Ј|12=draft}} mound burials.</ref> and the {{ill|Inaridai No.1 Kofun|ja|зЁІиҚ·еҸ°1еҸ·еҸӨеўі|Inaridai No.1 Kofun=Inaridai No.1 Kofun|lt=Inaritai No.1 Kofun|12=draft}}, which yielded an iron sword inscribed with the royal title {{ill|ЕҢkimi|ja|жІ»еӨ©дёӢеӨ§зҺӢ|12=draft}}.<ref>While some scholars attribute the title to the Yamato court, others link it to the chief buried in the nearby {{ill|Anegasaki Twin Mounds|ja|е§үеҙҺдәҢеӯҗеЎҡеҸӨеўі|1=Anesaki Futagozuka Kofun|12=draft}}.</ref> These indicate close ties with the {{ill|Yamato Court|ja|гғӨгғһгғҲзҺӢжЁ©|12=draft}}. In addition, the "{{ill|ManyЕҚshЕ«|ja|дёҮи‘үйӣҶ|12=draft}}" (Volume 14) includes an Eastern song that begins with "Natsuma pulls at the seacoast of KaijЕҚ Lagoon, the boat lingers on the shore as night deepens," suggesting its importance as a hub for waterway traffic.
The placement of {{ill|Musha no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|жӯҰзӨҫеӣҪйҖ |12=draft}} territory between Kamitsu Unakami and {{ill|Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|дёӢжө·дёҠеӣҪйҖ |12=draft}} regions implies that the establishment of KokuzЕҚ governance in the BЕҚsЕҚ Peninsula occurred in stages. By the 5th century, the Kamitsu Unakami KokuzЕҚ and Shimotsu Unakami KokuzЕҚ collectively exerted influence from central Chiba through parts of modern {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|иҢЁеҹҺзңҢ|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|еҹјзҺүзңҢ|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Tokyo|ja|жқұдә¬йғҪ|12=draft}}, a domain sometimes called "Greater Unakami Kuni."
